Homberg, a friend of Moses Mendelssohn and other members of the Haskalah movement, was charged by the Kaiser to establish modern Jewish school to replace the traditional learning institutes. This book was written in 1808 as a textbook, in which the principles of Jewish faith are presented, mostly based on arguments by Maimonides.
